@node "About" "About RaXchange"

                      =========
                        @{fg shine}About@{fg text}
                      =========


 I decided to write this program because on the internet you
 usually always run into someone from another country talking
 about how much something costs in there currency.  I included
 the shell based version of RaXchange in this archive just in
 case someone found a use for it.

 So RaXchange was born!  You might ask what the Ra is for?
 Anything I make will have Ra in front of it which means Roy's
 Amiga Xchange program.

 RaXchange and all future projects to come from RaSoft are
 writen in AmigaE, the coolest little language for the Amiga.


 Later,

 Roy(AK)

 @{i}@{fg fill}-Future-@{ui}@{fg text}

 I plan on making it so if you want to add a new currency you
 can just add it to the data file so you can add as many as
 you like or remove any you don't want.  Also to come in the
 next release the ability to set the default type and final
 types!
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Using RaXchange   "

                      =========
                       @{fg shine} Usage@{fg text}
                      =========


 @{fg fill}Using RaXchange:@{fg text}

 1) Inter the amount were it says amount! It can be fractional
    like 20.48 followed with a return.

 2) Next set the type to whatever the currency is you want to
    convert from the default being USD.

 3) Then set the final type to what you want it converted to.

 4) Finally press calculate and it will open a window with the
    final output in it!

 So that you know which country each curency code stands for
 I added the Curency Chart in the menu options.


 @{fg fill}Using RaXchangeCLI:@{fg text}

 RaXchangeCLI <amount> type=<Initial type> finaltype=<converting to>

 For Example to change 20 US dollars to German Marks you would use
 this command line.

 RaXchangeCLI 20 type=USD finaltype=GER



 @{b}-Data File-@{ub}

 Make sure there is a file in the program directory called data.
 This goes for both versions of RaXchange, shell and GUI. This
 contains the current exchange rates. You can update these rates
 which do change yourself. Go to the following site and obtaining
 a file which has a list of the current ratings. This particular
 site updates only once a month.

 @{u}gopher://gopher.undp.org/00/uncurr/exch_rates@{uu}

 A future version will contain a program to update the data file
 for you.
@endnode

